values.description:
e247b30 replaces the robonaut 2 model with the most recent version generated from https://gitlab.com/nasa-jsc-robotics/r2_description (6/29/17). Besides generating the robonaut urdf and converting it to an sdf, I made minimal changes:

1. Added an xml version tag.

2. Changed the baseplate collision mesh scale from `0.01 0.01 0.01` to `1 1 1` so that the model does not fall over.

3. Created a separate collision mesh for the base `Stanchion_Baseplate_Collision.dae` so that it sits flush with the ground.

Although the new and old models appear nearly identical (left and right respectively in the GIF below), there are many changes if you look at a diff. Even inertia parameters [have been changed](
https://gitlab.com/nasa-jsc-robotics/r2_description/commit/8d99d3e4b1dc0646f1b6c9cca4fc36a299d0e24d).

![robonaut.gif](data/bitbucket.org/repo/Mrn8xK7/images/1116711693-robonaut.gif)

One improvement of the updated model is that the joint limits all enclose `0.0` (the starting angles). The old model has a few joint limits that have negative upper bounds, which cause it to twitch  (see above) even when in zero gravity and not in contact with the ground plane.

summary.html:
e247b30 replaces the robonaut 2 model with the most recent version generated from https://gitlab.com/nasa-jsc-robotics/r2_description (6/29/17). Besides generating the robonaut urdf and converting it to an sdf, I made minimal changes:

  1. Added an xml version tag.

  2. Changed the baseplate collision mesh scale from 0.01 0.01 0.01 to 1 1 1 so that the model does not fall over.

  3. Created a separate collision mesh for the base Stanchion_Baseplate_Collision.dae so that it sits flush with the ground.

Although the new and old models appear nearly identical (left and right respectively in the GIF below), there are many changes if you look at a diff. Even inertia parameters have been changed.

One improvement of the updated model is that the joint limits all enclose 0.0 (the starting angles). The old model has a few joint limits that have negative upper bounds, which cause it to twitch (see above) even when in zero gravity and not in contact with the ground plane.

values.description:
I have seen the following error messages lately:
~~~
[Err] [ModelDatabase.cc:390] Unable to parse model.config for model[http://gazebosim.org/models/calibration_plane]
[Err] [ModelDatabase.cc:390] Unable to parse model.config for model[http://gazebosim.org/models/checkerboard_plane]
[Err] [ModelDatabase.cc:390] Unable to parse model.config for model[http://gazebosim.org/models/spectrum_plane]
~~~

The errors occur  when TiXml fails to parse the config files with multi-line description fields. It may fail to read the files [here](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/gazebo/src/1054201b80f7768d4f163a73df137a7ecc9e2e3e/gazebo/common/ModelDatabase.cc?at=default&fileviewer=file-view-default#ModelDatabase.cc-373) but succeed [in sdformat](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/sdformat/src/06eff281aba7a67a75f046578b925e3ca57ef4bc/src/parser.cc?at=default&fileviewer=file-view-default#parser.cc-594) because ModelDatabase.cc uses `Parse(string)` while sdformat's parser.cc uses `LoadFile(path)`.

This pull request removes the errors by converting the multi-line descriptions into single lines.

It may fail to read the files [here](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/gazebo/src/1054201b80f7768d4f163a73df137a7ecc9e2e3e/gazebo/common/ModelDatabase.cc?at=default&fileviewer=file-view-default#ModelDatabase.cc-373) but succeed [in sdformat](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/sdformat/src/06eff281aba7a67a75f046578b925e3ca57ef4bc/src/parser.cc?at=default&fileviewer=file-view-default#parser.cc-594) because ModelDatabase.cc uses `Parse(string)` while sdformat's parser.cc uses `LoadFile(path)`.

summary.html:
I have seen the following error messages lately:

[Err] [ModelDatabase.cc:390] Unable to parse model.config for model[http://gazebosim.org/models/calibration_plane]
[Err] [ModelDatabase.cc:390] Unable to parse model.config for model[http://gazebosim.org/models/checkerboard_plane]
[Err] [ModelDatabase.cc:390] Unable to parse model.config for model[http://gazebosim.org/models/spectrum_plane]

The errors occur when TiXml fails to parse the config files with multi-line description fields. It may fail to read the files here but succeed in sdformat because ModelDatabase.cc uses Parse(string) while sdformat's parser.cc uses LoadFile(path).

This pull request removes the errors by converting the multi-line descriptions into single lines.

Creating a pull request with your model means everyone has access to the model and can use it in their simulations. I'm going to close this PR since this model already exists.

Maybe this is a good opportunity to use model versions? I'm not sure if they are actually parsed by Gazebo.

If we merge this like this, note to whoever was relying on the houses the previous size, if you'd like to keep using the old size, you can paste the old SDF's `<model>` element directly into your world.

New sizes now fit adults:

![house1.png](data/bitbucket.org/repo/EgGzpd/images/1823572454-house1.png)

![house2.png](data/bitbucket.org/repo/EgGzpd/images/1771793855-house2.png)

![house3new.png](data/bitbucket.org/repo/EgGzpd/images/1725378725-house3new.png)

And `house_1` now matches its collapsed version (`collapsed_house`):

![house1col.png](data/bitbucket.org/repo/EgGzpd/images/1840508864-house1col.png)
